{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:28:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:28:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14179"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14179"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.23,0.12,0.49,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6862"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54542"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6862"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14179"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40051"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1623"},{"type":"tags","id":"2338"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43499"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54542"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parent after sustaining an injury to his right ring finger during a basketball game two hours ago. He reports that the ball hit the tip of his extended finger, causing it to bend suddenly. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The distal phalanx of his right ring finger is flexed and he is unable to actively extend it at the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint. There is mild swelling and tenderness over the dorsal aspect of the DIP joint, but the skin is intact. X-ray reveals a small avulsion fracture at the base of the distal phalanx, involving less than 30% of the articular surface.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical fixation of the avulsion fracture","Splinting in extension for 2 weeks","Buddy taping to the adjacent finger","Splinting in extension for 6-8 weeks","Cast immobilisation of the entire hand"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a closed bony mallet finger injury, as evidenced by the small avulsion fracture on X-ray and intact skin. Mallet finger occurs when there is forced flexion of an extended finger, typically caused by a ball hitting the fingertip. This results in disruption of the extensor tendon at its insertion into the base of the distal phalanx, sometimes with an associated avulsion fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate management for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Esplinting in extension for 6-8 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the first-line treatment for closed mallet injuries with small bony fragments involving less than 30% of the articular surface. The splint should keep the DIP joint in slight hyperextension while allowing free movement of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint. Continuous splinting is crucial for proper healing, and the splint should be worn at all times, even during bathing, for 6-8 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that bony mallet injuries, such as in this case, generally have more favourable outcomes compared to purely tendinous mallet injuries. This is due to the better blood supply in bony injuries, which can lead to faster and more reliable healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical fixation of the avulsion fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is generally not necessary for closed mallet injuries with small bony fragments (\u0026lt;30% of the articular surface). Surgery is typically reserved for cases with large bony fragments (\u0026gt;30% of the articular surface), volar subluxation of the distal phalanx, open injuries, or failed conservative treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplinting in extension for 2 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for proper healing. Mallet injuries, especially those with bony involvement, require a longer period of continuous splinting to allow for adequate healing and to prevent a permanent flexion deformity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBuddy taping\u003C/strong\u003E to the adjacent finger is not appropriate for a mallet injury as it does not maintain the DIP joint in extension, which is necessary for proper healing of the extensor tendon and bony fragment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECast immobilisation of the entire hand\u003C/strong\u003E is overly restrictive and unnecessary for a mallet injury. It would limit function more than required and potentially lead to stiffness in unaffected joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the initial 6-8 week period of continuous splinting, the patient would typically transition to night splinting for an additional 2-4 weeks. Regular follow-up with repeat X-rays is important to ensure proper healing of both the soft tissue and bony components, and to adjust treatment if necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that management would differ for open mallet injuries. These typically require urgent surgical intervention to prevent infection and ensure proper healing. Similarly, purely tendinous mallet injuries without bony involvement are also treated with splinting, but may require a longer duration of immobilisation due to the less favourable blood supply compared to bony injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mallet finger with bony involvement (avulsion fracture) is an injury to the extensor tendon at the distal interphalangeal joint, often caused by forced flexion of an extended finger.","Conservative management with continuous splinting for 6-8 weeks is the first-line treatment for closed mallet injuries with small bony fragments (\u003C30% of the articular surface).","Bony mallet injuries generally have more favourable outcomes compared to tendinous mallet injuries due to better blood supply."],"references":["Bobjgalindo, CC BY-SA 4.0 \u003Chttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0\u003E, via Wikimedia Commons","Khera B, Chang C, Bhat W. An overview of mallet finger injuries. Acta Biomed. 2021 Nov 3;92(5):e2021246. doi: 10.23750/abm.v92i5.11731. PMID: 34738569; PMCID: PMC8689306."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40051"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14179"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21023"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21023"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WXXufLRgD2WZbQrINShgZex4qLYqcb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WXXufLRgD2WZbQrINShgZex4qLYqcb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":709,"height":819}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40051"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-07T10:45:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-07T10:4